<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,151,320]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
The hyperdiverse, cosmopolitan genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kugelann" authorityYear="1794" box="[598,710,151,176]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[598,710,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well defined by the following autapomorphic morphological characteristics: 1) presence of a labral-mandibular interlocking device (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins" box="[970,1125,188,213]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1989) Adelphydraena, new genus, and two new species from Venezuela, and remarks on phylogenetic relationships within the subtribe Hydraenina (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 102, 447 - 457." type="journal article" year="1989">Perkins 1989</bibRefCitation>
), 2) mentum with an acute median projection anteriorly (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins" box="[503,663,223,248]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1989) Adelphydraena, new genus, and two new species from Venezuela, and remarks on phylogenetic relationships within the subtribe Hydraenina (Coleoptera: Hydraenidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 102, 447 - 457." type="journal article" year="1989">Perkins 1989</bibRefCitation>
), 3) various complex sensilla (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins" box="[1036,1194,223,248]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997) Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">Perkins 1997</bibRefCitation>
), and 4) specialized features of the exocrine secretion delivery system (
<bibRefCitation author="Perkins" box="[755,913,260,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" refString="Perkins, P. D. (1997) Life on the effective bubble: exocrine secretion delivery systems (ESDS) and the evolution and classification of beetles in the family Hydraenidae (Insecta: Coleoptera). Annals of Carnegie Museum, 66 (2), 89 - 207." type="journal article" year="1997">Perkins 1997</bibRefCitation>
). There is general agreement among current workers that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kugelann" authorityYear="1794" box="[297,409,295,320]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[297,409,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is monophyletic, based on these morphological characters (for example, JÃ¤ch 
<emphasis box="[1285,1341,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">et al.</emphasis>
2000).
</paragraph>
